The Borno State chapter of the Nigeria Union of Pensioners (NUP) has implored the Pension Transitional Arrangement Directorate (PTAD) to look into the plight of its members who lost their pension documents while fleeing the Boko Haram attacks on their respective communities. The NUP made the appeal yesterday in Maiduguri during PTAD Fourth Phase of Parastatals Pensioner Verification Exercise For Pensioners and Next of Kin (NOK) of all federally funded Parastatals, Agencies and Institutions under the Defined  Benefit  Scheme (DBS). The Secretary of NUP in Borno, Bukar Alhaji, complained that members who present affidavit of loss of documents are turned down from being captured and verified due to inability to present photocopies of documents. The Borneo NUP secretary said: “I am appealing to PTAD with regard to Borno state to consider the plight of my members who lost their Pension documents to the Boko Haram insurgency in the verification exercise.  We have problem of insurgency and many of our pensioners in the process of running for their lives, lost their documents.” Addressing pensioners  during the exercise, the Executive Director PTAD, Sharon Ikeazor said a new process had been put on ground whereby on the field computation of pensioners is carried out and complaints resolved while staff are on the field. 111 railway pensioners not on payroll since 2005 NUP Pensioners demand payment of 42 months arrears FG commences verification of pensioners in North-East Dear Esteemed reader, As part of our drive to keep improving the content of our newspaper, we are conducting a readership survey to enable us serve you better. Kindly take two minutes of your time to fill in this questionnaire. Thank you for your time. Click here to begin